South African Stocks: Adcock Ingram, BHP Billiton, Sasol, Taste Are Active

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a   a n d   M i k e   C o h e n
-- 
2011-05-24T15:33:49Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-24/south-african-stocks-advance-in-opening-trading-led-by-bhp-sasol-and-mtn.html
The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index
rose the most since May 10, adding 386.52, or 1.2 percent, to
31,731.05 by the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Adcock Ingram Holdings Ltd. (AIP)  , Africa’s largest
over-the-counter drug manufacturer, advanced for a second day,
increasing 1.40 rand, or 2.3 percent, to 61.50 rand. The company
is seeking acquisitions in West Africa to take advantage of
economic growth in the region, Chief Executive Officer Jonathan
Louw said.  BHP Billiton Plc (BIL)  , the world’s largest mining
company, snapped four days of losses, jumping 3.90 rand, or 1.5
percent, to 265.05 rand. Copper rose as much as 1.8 percent to
$8,956 a metric ton on the London Metal Exchange, after Goldman
Sachs Group Inc. said it’s turning “more bullish” on raw
materials. Yesterday the metal had the biggest drop in almost
two weeks.  Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, snapped two days of losses, increasing 4.86
rand, or 1.4 percent, to 351.70 rand. Oil rose as much as 2.3
percent to $99.77 a barrel.  Stefanutti Stocks Holdings Ltd. (SSK)  , a South African
construction and engineering company, fell 20 cents, or 1.6
percent, to 12 rand. Net income for the year ended Feb. 28 fell
13 percent to 333 million rand ($47.6 million), the company said
in a regulatory statement.  Taste Holdings Ltd. (TAS)  , a restaurant operator,
climbed the most since at least June 2006, jumping 15 cents, or
27 percent, to 70 cents. Earnings per share climbed 15 percent
to 10.7 cents in the year ended Feb. 28, the company said.  To contact the reporters on this story:
